    "osso buco": `Ingredients:
        4 veal shanks, about 1 1/2 inches thick
        Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
        All-purpose flour, for dredging
        4 tbsp unsalted butter
        2 tbsp olive oil
        1 onion, finely chopped
        2 carrots, finely chopped
        2 celery stalks, finely chopped
        4 cloves garlic, minced
        1 cup dry white wine
        1 can (14.5 oz) diced tomatoes
        1 cup chicken or beef broth
        2 sprigs fresh rosemary
        2 sprigs fresh thyme
        2 bay leaves
        Gremolata (optional):
        Zest of 1 lemon
        2 tbsp chopped fresh parsley
        2 cloves garlic, minced
        Instructions:
        Season the veal shanks generously with salt and freshly ground black pepper, then dredge them in flour, shaking off any excess.
        In a large skillet or Dutch oven, heat the butter and olive oil over medium-high heat. Once hot, add the veal shanks to the skillet and cook until browned on both sides, about 5 minutes per side. Remove the shanks from the skillet and set aside.
        In the same skillet, add the chopped onion, carrots, celery, and minced garlic. Cook, stirring occasionally, until the vegetables are softened and lightly browned, about 5-7 minutes.
        Deglaze the skillet with the dry white wine, scraping up any browned bits from the bottom of the pan.
        Stir in the diced tomatoes and chicken or beef broth. Bring the mixture to a simmer.
        Return the browned veal shanks to the skillet, nestling them into the vegetable mixture.
        Add the fresh rosemary, thyme, and bay leaves to the skillet.
        Cover the skillet or Dutch oven with a lid and reduce the heat to low. Let the osso buco simmer gently for 1 1/2 to 2 hours, or until the veal is tender and falling off the bone.
        While the osso buco is cooking, prepare the gremolata by mixing together the lemon zest, chopped fresh parsley, and minced garlic in a small bowl.
        Once the veal is tender, remove the skillet from the heat and discard the bay leaves and herb sprigs.
        Serve the osso buco hot, garnished with the prepared gremolata, and accompanied by risotto, polenta, or crusty bread for soaking up the flavorful sauce.
        Enjoy the rich and comforting Osso Buco, a classic Italian dish!`,
