        Mushroom filling: 2 cups finely chopped mushrooms (such as cremini or button), 1/2 cup ricotta cheese, 1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese, 1 garlic clove (minced), 1 tbsp olive oil, salt, pepper, and fresh herbs (such as thyme or rosemary)
        Instructions:
        Prepare the pasta dough: On a clean work surface, mound the flour and make a well in the center. Crack the eggs into the well and add the salt.
        Using a fork, gradually incorporate the flour into the eggs until a dough forms. Knead the dough for about 5-10 minutes until smooth and elastic.
        Wrap the dough in plastic wrap and let it rest at room temperature for at least 30 minutes.
        Prepare the filling: In a mixing bowl, combine the ingredients for the filling of your choice and mix until well combined.
        Roll out the pasta dough using a pasta machine or a rolling pin until very thin (about 1/8 inch thick).
        Place teaspoon-sized portions of the filling onto half of the rolled-out dough, leaving space between each portion.
        Brush the edges of the dough with water and fold the other half of the dough over the filling.
        Press down around each mound of filling to seal the edges and remove any air pockets.
        Use a ravioli cutter or a knife to cut the ravioli into squares or circles.
        Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Cook the ravioli in batches for 2-3 minutes, or until they float to the surface.
        Remove the cooked ravioli with a slotted spoon and transfer them to a serving dish.
        Serve the ravioli hot with your favorite sauce and garnish with grated Parmesan cheese and fresh herbs, if desired.`,
    "pesto genovese": `Ingredients:
        2 cups fresh basil leaves, packed
        1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese
        1/4 cup pine nuts or walnuts, toasted
        2 garlic cloves, peeled
        1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
        Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
        Instructions:
        In a food processor, combine the basil leaves, grated Parmesan cheese, toasted pine nuts or walnuts, and garlic cloves.
        Pulse the ingredients until coarsely chopped.
        With the food processor running, slowly drizzle in the olive oil until the pesto reaches your desired consistency. You may need to stop and scrape down the sides of the bowl with a spatula.
        Season the pesto with salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste. Adjust the seasoning if necessary.
        Transfer the pesto to a bowl or airtight container. If not using immediately, cover the surface of the pesto with a thin layer of olive oil to prevent it from oxidizing and turning brown.
        Serve the pesto with cooked pasta, spread on sandwiches, or use it as a dip or sauce for vegetables.
        Enjoy the vibrant flavor of homemade Pesto Genovese, packed with fresh basil, Parmesan cheese, and aromatic garlic!`,
