        Ladle the hot minestrone into serving bowls and garnish with grated Parmesan cheese, if desired.
        Serve the minestrone soup hot with crusty bread for a comforting and satisfying meal!`,
    "cioppino": `Ingredients:
        2 tbsp olive oil
        1 onion, diced
        2 celery stalks, diced
        1 red bell pepper, diced
        4 garlic cloves, minced
        1/2 cup dry white wine
        1 can (28 oz) crushed tomatoes
        2 cups seafood or fish stock
        1/2 tsp dried oregano
        1/2 tsp dried thyme
        1 bay leaf
        Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
        1 lb mixed seafood (such as shrimp, scallops, mussels, clams, and fish fillets), cleaned and deveined
        Chopped fresh parsley, for garnish
        Crusty bread, for serving
        Instructions:
        Heat the olive oil in a large pot or Dutch oven over medium heat. Add the diced onion, celery, and red bell pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until the vegetables are softened, about 5-7 minutes.
        Add the minced garlic to the pot and cook for an additional 1-2 minutes, until fragrant.
        Pour in the dry white wine and bring to a simmer. Let it cook for a few minutes to reduce slightly.
        Stir in the crushed tomatoes, seafood or fish stock, dried oregano, dried thyme, and bay leaf. Season with salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste.
        Bring the mixture to a simmer, then reduce the heat to low and let it simmer gently for about 20-30 minutes to allow the flavors to meld.
        Add the mixed seafood to the pot and cook until the seafood is cooked through and the mussels and clams have opened, about 5-7 minutes.
        Discard any mussels or clams that do not open.
        Taste and adjust the seasoning if needed.
        Ladle the hot cioppino into serving bowls, garnish with chopped fresh parsley, and serve immediately with crusty bread for soaking up the flavorful broth.
        Enjoy the delicious and comforting flavors of homemade Cioppino, a classic Italian-American seafood stew!`,
    "trdelník": `Ingredients:
        1 lb (about 4 cups) all-purpose flour
        1/4 cup granulated sugar
        1/2 tsp salt
        1/2 cup warm water
        2 tsp active dry yeast
        1/2 cup unsalted butter, melted
        1/2 cup ground walnuts or almonds
        1/2 cup granulated sugar mixed with 1 tsp ground cinnamon, for coating
        Instructions:
        In a small bowl, dissolve the active dry yeast in the warm water and let it sit for about 5-10 minutes, or until foamy.
        In a large mixing bowl, combine the flour, granulated sugar, and salt. Make a well in the center and pour in the yeast mixture.
        Mix the ingredients together until a dough forms. Knead the dough for about 5-10 minutes until smooth and elastic.
        Place the dough in a lightly greased bowl, cover with plastic wrap or a clean kitchen towel, and let it rise in a warm, draft-free place for about 1-2 hours, or until doubled in size.
        Preheat your oven to 350°F (175°C).
        Punch down the risen dough and divide it into equal portions.
        Roll each portion of dough into a long rope, about 1 inch in diameter.
        Wrap the dough rope around a wooden or metal trdelník mold in a spiral pattern, leaving a small gap between each turn.
        Brush the wrapped dough with melted butter and sprinkle with ground walnuts or almonds.
        Place the trdelník molds on a baking sheet and bake in the preheated oven for 20-25 minutes, or until golden brown and cooked through.
        Remove the baked trdelník from the oven and let them cool slightly.
        Carefully slide the trdelník off the molds and roll them in the cinnamon-sugar mixture until evenly coated.
        Serve the warm trdelník as a delightful sweet treat, enjoying the crispy exterior and soft, fluffy interior!`,
