        3 cups cooked rice, cooled (preferably day-old rice)
        2 tbsp vegetable oil
        2 eggs, beaten
        1 onion, diced
        2 cloves garlic, minced
        1 cup mixed vegetables (such as diced carrots, peas, and corn)
        1/4 cup soy sauce
        2 tbsp oyster sauce
        Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
        Chopped green onions, for garnish
        Sesame seeds, for garnish (optional)
        Instructions:
        Heat 1 tablespoon of vegetable oil in a large skillet or wok over medium heat. Pour in the beaten eggs and scramble until cooked through. Remove the scrambled eggs from the skillet and set aside.
        In the same skillet, heat the remaining tablespoon of vegetable oil. Add the diced onion and minced garlic, and cook until softened and fragrant, about 2-3 minutes.
        Stir in the mixed vegetables and cook until tender, about 3-4 minutes.
        Add the cooked rice to the skillet, breaking up any clumps with a spatula. Cook, stirring frequently, until the rice is heated through and starting to turn golden brown, about 5-7 minutes.
        Return the scrambled eggs to the skillet and stir to combine with the rice and vegetables.
        Pour the soy sauce and oyster sauce over the rice mixture. Stir well to evenly coat everything in the sauce.
        Season the fried rice with salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste. Stir in chopped green onions.
        Garnish the fried rice with sesame seeds (if using) and serve hot as a delicious and satisfying meal or side dish.
        Enjoy the savory and flavorful Fried Rice as a comforting and versatile dish!`,
    "tanghulu": `Ingredients:
        Skewered fruits (such as strawberries, grapes, kiwi slices, pineapple chunks, or mandarin orange segments)
        1 cup granulated sugar
        1/2 cup water
        Instructions:
        Prepare the skewered fruits by threading them onto wooden skewers or bamboo sticks. Make sure the fruits are evenly distributed on the skewers.
        In a small saucepan, combine the granulated sugar and water. Heat over medium heat, stirring constantly, until the sugar has completely dissolved.
        Increase the heat to medium-high and bring the sugar syrup to a gentle boil. Continue to cook without stirring until the syrup reaches the hard crack stage, about 300°F (150°C) on a candy thermometer.
        Remove the saucepan from the heat and let the sugar syrup cool slightly for a few minutes.
        Dip each skewered fruit into the sugar syrup, coating it evenly with the hot syrup. Be careful as the syrup will be very hot.
        Allow the excess syrup to drip off the fruits, then place the coated fruits on a parchment-lined baking sheet to cool and harden.
        Let the tanghulu cool completely before serving. Enjoy the crunchy and sweet Tanghulu as a delightful snack or dessert!`,
